    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/vr-absolute-hemolysis-index-2023",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Absolute hemolysis index validation — five operating points with Monte Carlo UQ",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/hemolysis-bench-measurements-2022",
      "description": "This validation result documents the comparison of CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values against in-vitro measurements conducted at an ISO 17025-accredited laboratory across five flow-speed operating points (2–6 L/min, 2500–4500 RPM). The experimental campaign used a modified ASTM F1841 protocol with a porcine blood surrogate (haematocrit 33±2%, temperature 37±0.5 °C). CFD predictions were obtained using the Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law damage model integrated along Lagrangian particle trajectories seeded at the inlet plane. Monte Carlo uncertainty propagation (N=2000 samples) was applied to inlet boundary conditions, fluid viscosity, and damage-model exponents, yielding 95% prediction intervals for NIH at each operating point. Agreement between simulation median and experimental mean was within 18% at four of five points; the fifth point (6 L/min, 4500 RPM) showed a 31% over-prediction attributed to recirculation zone sensitivity. The assessment team reviewed raw NIH time-series, mesh independence evidence, and turbulence model sensitivity sweeps before recording this result. All artefacts are archived in the project document management system under reference VAD-VV-2023-HEM-007."
    }
  ],
